  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "In medias res (Latin: \u0026ldquo;in the middle of things\u0026rdquo;) is the technique of beginning a narrative in the middle of the action rather than at the chronological beginning. Homer\u0026rsquo;s Iliad opens in the ninth year of the Trojan War, not with Paris\u0026rsquo;s judgment or Helen\u0026rsquo;s abduction. The reader is dropped into a conflict already underway and must orient themselves through context, exposition, and inference.\nIn medias res works because it prioritizes engagement over orientation. A story that begins \u0026ldquo;John was born in 1952 in a small town in Ohio\u0026rdquo; asks the reader to wait for the story to begin. A story that begins \u0026ldquo;John pushed open the door and found the apartment empty — furniture gone, clothes gone, the only thing remaining a note on the kitchen counter\u0026rdquo; has already begun. The reader\u0026rsquo;s questions (Whose apartment? Why empty? What does the note say?) pull them forward.\n",
